    en: "Some employers call workers 'independent contractors' to avoid paying minimum wage, overtime, unemployment insurance, workers' compensation, and payroll taxes. If the employer controls how, when, and where a worker performs the job, the worker is usually an employee — regardless of what the paperwork says. New York's Construction Industry Fair Play Act (Labor Law 861-c) adds a strict presumption for construction workers. The NYS Department of Labor's Joint Enforcement Task Force on Employee Misclassification investigates these cases. A misclassified worker can recover back wages, unemployment, and workers' comp benefits. Retaliation for reporting is separately illegal under LL 215."
